    <item>
      <title>What Are We Building?</title>
      <link>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/what-are-we-building/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/what-are-we-building/</guid>
      <description>Together we&amp;rsquo;ll build Conduit, a social blogging site a la Medium. We&amp;rsquo;re tasked with building a minimum viable product — something functionally complete and stable, but not over-engineered — with at least a few tests.
Our lovely project management team, Thinkster, has provided us with a few resources to help guide development:
 A detailed spec which describes the requirements for the application A complete API, available in hosted version and described with a thoughtful API spec Pre-built Bootstrap 4 styles available via CDN and sample HTML templates for our pages A demo frontend already built in another language to verify things are looking good  With the spec in hand we&amp;rsquo;re ready to step into the design process.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Design Data &amp; Pure Functions</title>
      <link>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/design-data-pure-functions/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/design-data-pure-functions/</guid>
      <description>PureScript has a best-in-class type system with powerful features like algebraic data types, generics, row types, type classes. Let&amp;rsquo;s put this type system to work to help us represent the the data our application will use to support our use cases.
We&amp;rsquo;ll sometimes use primitive data like strings, booleans, and numbers to represent values in our application. But most data we&amp;rsquo;ll work with have meaning in our application beyond being a boolean or a string.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Push Effects To The Edges</title>
      <link>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/push-effects-to-the-edges/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/push-effects-to-the-edges/</guid>
      <description>So far we&amp;rsquo;ve spent all our time writing core data types and the types of functions that will operate on them. We haven&amp;rsquo;t implemented any of these functions yet. We could go ahead and implement any pure functions we&amp;rsquo;d like, but we should pause before implementing any non-pure functions (functions with Aff or Effect in their type). We need to be careful about how we design effects in our system.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Using Halogen Components</title>
      <link>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/using-halogen-components/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://thomashoneyman.com/guides/real-world-halogen/using-halogen-components/</guid>
      <description>Finally, let&amp;rsquo;s briefly discuss Halogen. Halogen is a declarative, type-safe UI library for PureScript applications. It&amp;rsquo;s the most commonly used framework for applications implemented entirely in PureScript, while projects that depend heavily on the React ecosystem tend to use purescript-react-basic and purescript-react. If you&amp;rsquo;re curious what code written with those libraries look like, you might want to read my article on writing PureScript React components to replace JavaScript code.</description>
    </item>
    
