      <description>Optics are among the most rewarding tools in functional programming. You can use them to manipulate values within data structures without boilerplate &amp;ndash; you just need a few types and functions from an optics library like profunctor-lenses.
Consider working with a deeply-nested data structure like this one:
type NestedData = Maybe (Array { foo :: Tuple String (Either Int Boolean), bar :: String }) Faced with this type, ask yourself:</description>
